      "question": "A vertical pole of length $h$ stands on the ground. At a point $P$ on the ground, the angle of elevation of the top of the pole is $60^\\circ$. If the distance from the foot of the pole to point $P$ is $d$, and a point $Q$ is located on the same horizontal line such that the angle of elevation of the top of the pole is $30^\\circ$, then the distance $PQ$ is equal to:",
      "answer": "(C)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Let the pole be $AB$ with height $h$ and $B$ on the ground.",
          "In $\\triangle ABP$, $\\tan(60^\\circ) = \\frac{AB}{BP} = \\frac{h}{d}$, so $d = \\frac{h}{\\sqrt{3}}$.",
          "In $\\triangle ABQ$, $\\tan(30^\\circ) = \\frac{AB}{BQ} = \\frac{h}{BQ}$, so $BQ = h\\sqrt{3}$.",
          "The distance $PQ = BQ - BP = h\\sqrt{3} - \\frac{h}{\\sqrt{3}}$.",
          "Simplify $PQ = h \\left( \\frac{3-1}{\\sqrt{3}} \\right) = \\frac{2h}{\\sqrt{3}}$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$BP = h \\cot(60^\\circ) = \\frac{h}{\\sqrt{3}} \\\\ BQ = h \\cot(30^\\circ) = h\\sqrt{3} \\\\ PQ = BQ - BP = h\\sqrt{3} - \\frac{h}{\\sqrt{3}} \\\\ PQ = \\frac{3h - h}{\\sqrt{3}} = \\frac{2h}{\\sqrt{3}}$"
      },
      "topic": "Some Applications of Trigonometry",
      "subtopic": "Height and Distance",
      "marks": 1,
